    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I guess it depends on what would take more effort:\r\n\r\n- keeping the sharding code running at all times through the API changes\r\n- resurrecting it once\r\n\r\nIntuitively I'd say resurrecting once is easier, especially given that both the py-EVM and the sharding state execution model (-> alternative execution engines) will change. Also I would be surprised if there are no additional EVM changes coming. But I wasn't involved in the recent merges, so this is just my gut feeling, with no practical experience to justify it.",
